sections.english:
Monks, on one occasion, when I was first fully enlightened, I was dwelling at Uruvelā, on the bank of the Nerañjarā River, at the Goatherd's Banyan Tree. Then, monks, many brahmins—aged, old, venerable, well-advanced in years, having reached the full measure of their lives—approached me. Having approached, they exchanged greetings with me. After exchanging courteous and memorable talk, they sat down to one side. Seated to one side, monks, those brahmins said to me: ‘We have heard this, Master Gotama, that the ascetic Gotama does not greet, nor rise up for, nor invite with a seat, brahmins who are aged, old, venerable, well-advanced in years, having reached the full measure of their lives.’ ‘And that, Master Gotama, is indeed true. For Master Gotama does not greet, nor rise up for, nor invite with a seat, brahmins who are aged, old, venerable, well-advanced in years, having reached the full measure of their lives. This, Master Gotama, is not proper behavior.’

Then, monks, it occurred to me: ‘These venerable ones do not understand what makes one an elder, nor the qualities that make one an elder.’ Even if, monks, someone is old—eighty, ninety, or a hundred years of age by birth—and he is one who speaks at an inappropriate time, speaks what is untrue, speaks what is unbeneficial, speaks contrary to the Dhamma, speaks contrary to the Vinaya, and utters speech that is not worth storing, spoken at an inappropriate time, without reference, boundless, and unbeneficial. Then such a one is reckoned as ‘a foolish elder’.

Even if, monks, someone is young—with fresh, jet-black hair, endowed with the fortune of youth, in the prime of life. And he is one who speaks at an appropriate time, speaks what is true, speaks what is beneficial, speaks in accordance with the Dhamma, speaks in accordance with the Vinaya, and utters speech that is worth storing, spoken at an appropriate time, with reference, bounded, and beneficial. Then such a one is reckoned as ‘a wise elder’.

Monks, there are these four qualities that make one an elder. Which four? Here, monks, a bhikkhu is virtuous; he dwells restrained by the Pāṭimokkha restraint, perfect in conduct and domain, seeing danger in the slightest faults, undertaking and training in the training rules. He is learned, a preserver of what he has heard, a cumulative preserver of what he has heard. Those teachings that are good in the beginning, good in the middle, and good in the end, with their meaning and their phrasing, proclaiming a purely complete and purified holy life—such teachings are much heard by him, retained, familiarized verbally, contemplated mentally, and well-penetrated by understanding. He is a frequent obtainer, without difficulty, without trouble, of the four meditative absorptions (jhānas) which are of a higher mind and are dwellings in ease here and now. Through the destruction of the taints, he enters and dwells in the taintless liberation of mind and liberation by wisdom, having realized them for himself with direct knowledge in this very life. These, monks, are the four qualities that make one an elder.

One whose mind is agitated, who speaks much idle chatter;
Whose resolves are unconcentrated, a deluded person who delights not in the good Dhamma;
He is far from steadiness, with wrong view, disrespectful.

But one who is endowed with virtue, learned, and discerning;
Restrained and wise in the teachings, who sees the meaning with wisdom.

One who has gone beyond all phenomena, unhindered, discerning;
One who has abandoned birth and death, a complete practitioner of the holy life.

Him I call an elder, in whom there are no taints;
A bhikkhu whose taints are destroyed—he is called an elder.

At one time, the Blessed One was dwelling in Sāketa, at the Kālakarama Monastery. There, the Blessed One addressed the monks, saying: "Monks!" Those monks responded to the Blessed One, "Venerable Sir!" The Blessed One then spoke thus:

"Monks, whatever is seen, heard, sensed, cognized, attained, sought after, and investigated with the mind by the world with its devas, Māra, Brahmā, its ascetics and brahmins, its devas and humans – that I know. Monks, whatever is seen, heard, sensed, cognized, attained, sought after, and investigated with the mind by the world with its devas, Māra, Brahmā, its ascetics and brahmins, its devas and humans – that I have fully comprehended. That is known by the Tathāgata, yet the Tathāgata does not cling to it. Monks, if I were to say of that [same range of experience], 'I do not know that,' that would be a falsehood on my part. Monks, if I were to say of that [same range of experience], 'I both know it and do not know it,' that would likewise be similar. Monks, if I were to say of that [same range of experience], 'I neither know it nor do not know it,' that would be an impropriety on my part. Thus, Monks, having seen what is to be seen, the Tathāgata does not conceive of the seen, does not conceive of the unseen, does not conceive of what is to be seen, does not conceive of the seer; having heard what is to be heard, does not conceive of the heard, does not conceive of the unheard, does not conceive of what is to be heard, does not conceive of the hearer; having sensed what is to be sensed, does not conceive of the sensed, does not conceive of the unsensed, does not conceive of what is to be sensed, does not conceive of the sensor; having cognized what is to be cognized, does not conceive of the cognized, does not conceive of the uncognized, does not conceive of what is to be cognized, does not conceive of the cognizer. Thus, Monks, regarding phenomena seen, heard, sensed, and cognized, the Tathāgata is truly unperturbed. And I declare that there is no other unperturbed one more exalted or more sublime than this Unperturbed One."

"Whatever is seen, heard, or sensed,
That which others cling to as truth or falsity;
Among those, the Unperturbed One, fully restrained,
Does not incite another concerning truth or falsehood.
And having seen this barb beforehand,
By which beings are clinging and entrapped;
I know and see this just as it is;
For the Tathāgatas, there is no clinging."

Those monks, O bhikkhus, who are deceitful, stubborn, boastful, showy, haughty, and unconcentrated—those monks, O bhikkhus, are not truly mine. And those monks, O bhikkhus, are alienated from this Dhamma and Discipline, and they do not attain growth, development, and maturity in this Dhamma and Discipline. But those monks, O bhikkhus, who are without deceit, not boastful, wise, not stubborn, and well-concentrated—indeed, those monks, O bhikkhus, are truly mine. And those monks, O bhikkhus, are not alienated from this Dhamma and Discipline. And they attain growth, development, and maturity in this Dhamma and Discipline.

Deceitful, stubborn, boastful, showy, haughty, and unconcentrated;
They do not flourish in the Dhamma taught by the Perfectly Self-Awakened One.
Without deceit, not boastful, wise, not stubborn, and well-concentrated;
Indeed, they flourish in the Dhamma taught by the Perfectly Self-Awakened One.
